definitions: in or to a position under or lower than something
lower in rank, status, or importance than someone
not worthy of someone's dignity, status, or standards
examples: The treasure was buried beneath the sand
Fish swim beneath the surface
A sergeant ranks beneath a lieutenant
She works beneath the department head
Such behavior is beneath you
He considers the job beneath him

definitions: at the side of or next to someone or something
compared with or in comparison to something else
irrelevant to or having no connection with something
examples: She sat beside her mother
The house beside ours is for sale
My problems seem small beside yours
Beside this issue, everything else is minor
That's beside the point entirely
Your objection is beside the question

definitions: existing or happening before a particular time or event
more important than something else; taking precedence over
examples: Prior to the meeting, please read the report
No prior experience is necessary
Family takes prior claim over work
Prior obligations must be fulfilled first

definitions: in or toward the front; further forward in space
in or into the future; at a later time
before an expected time; more advanced than others
examples: Look straight ahead when driving
The road ahead is under construction
Difficult times lie ahead
We need to plan ahead
She's ahead in her studies
We're ahead of schedule

definitions: at or on the highest part or surface of something
in addition to something that makes a situation worse
at the maximum level or highest degree of something
examples: Put the star on top of the tree
Snow covered the mountain top
On top of everything else, it rained
He lost his job on top of being sick
She's at the top of her class
Drive at top speed

definitions: different from or not similar to something or someone
not typical or characteristic of someone's usual behavior
examples: Unlike her sister, she loves sports
This car is unlike any other
It's unlike him to be late
That comment was unlike her

definitions: according to or determined by particular circumstances or conditions
needing or relying on something else for support or existence
examples: The price varies depending on the size
Depending on weather, we'll go outside
Success is depending on your effort
We're depending on good weather

definitions: against another person or team in competition or legal action
as opposed to or in contrast with something else
examples: The case is Smith versus Jones
Tonight's game is Boston versus New York
It's quality versus quantity
Nature versus nurture debate

definitions: conditional upon or dependent on something else happening
likely to experience or be affected by something unpleasant
examples: Approval is subject to conditions
Plans are subject to change
The area is subject to flooding
He's subject to mood swings

definitions: regarding or concerning a particular subject (abbreviation)
about or on the subject of something in correspondence
examples: Re your email yesterday
Re: Meeting agenda
I'm writing re the job opening
Re our conversation last week
